      "subtitle": "Lawful and unlawful interview and application questions: discrimination, inherent requirements, and pre-employment checks in Australian recruitment",
      "summary": "In Australia, recruitment is governed by overlapping federal regimes, plus state/territory anti-discrimination laws. The Fair Work Act 2009 (Cth) s 351 makes it unlawful for an employer to take \"adverse action\" against a prospective employee (job applicant) because of a protected attribute — race, colour, sex, sexual orientation, breastfeeding, gender identity, intersex status, age, physical or mental disability, marital status, family or carer's responsibilities, pregnancy, religion, political opinion, national extraction, or social origin (and, since 2023 reforms, because the person is or has been subjected to family and domestic violence). The Sex Discrimination Act 1984, Disability Discrimination Act 1992, Racial Discrimination Act 1975 and Age Discrimination Act 2004 prohibit discrimination \"in the arrangements made for the purpose of determining who should be offered employment\" — which reaches interview questions, application forms and selection criteria. The practical rule for interviewers: ask only what is relevant to the inherent requirements of the role, ask all candidates the same job-related questions, and avoid personal, intrusive or irrelevant questions that touch protected attributes (e.g. age, marital status, pregnancy or plans to have children, religion, disability, country of origin). Where a candidate has disability, an employer must consider reasonable adjustments and may only decline on capacity grounds if, even with adjustments, the person cannot perform the genuine inherent requirements (and the adjustment is not \"unjustifiable hardship\"). Criminal-record questions are constrained by the Australian Human Rights Commission Act 1986 (under which criminal-record discrimination in employment is a ground of complaint to the Commission) — employers should only seek conviction information relevant to the inherent requirements and give the applicant a chance to explain. The Privacy Act 1988 (Australian Privacy Principles, esp. APP 3) limits collection on application forms to information reasonably necessary for the recruitment function; the employee-records exemption does NOT cover unsuccessful applicants, so applicant data must be handled compliantly. Employers must also verify the right to work in Australia (e.g. via VEVO) under the Migration Act 1958, with strengthened employer-compliance offences commencing in 2024. Finally, the Respect@Work positive duty (Sex Discrimination Act 1984, commenced 12 December 2022) requires all employers to take reasonable and proportionate measures to eliminate sex discrimination and sexual harassment — relevant to how interviews are conducted. This is general information, not legal advice.",
