      "title": "Reference & pre-employment checks",
      "subtitle": "Lawful reference checking and pre-employment checks under Australian law (2026)",
      "summary": "When a small Australian business contacts referees or runs background checks on a job applicant, several bodies of law operate at once. (1) Privacy: an employer collecting an applicant's personal information (resume, references, transcripts, check results) is generally governed by the Privacy Act 1988 (Cth) and the Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) if the business is a \"covered\" organisation (most with annual turnover over $3M, plus some others regardless of turnover). The \"employee records exemption\" does NOT apply at the recruitment stage — OAIC guidance confirms it only covers acts directly related to a current or former employment relationship, not prospective employees and not unsuccessful applicants — so applicants retain privacy rights, including a general right to access information held about them (which can include a referee's report). APP 3 limits collection to what is reasonably necessary, and sensitive information (e.g. health information, and criminal record information where it is sensitive information) generally needs the applicant's consent (APP 3.3), subject to limited exceptions. (2) Discrimination: the Fair Work Act 2009 (Cth) makes it unlawful to take \"adverse action\" (including refusing to employ, or discriminating in the terms of an offer) against a prospective employee because of a protected attribute (race, colour, sex, sexual orientation, breastfeeding, gender identity, intersex status, age, physical or mental disability, marital status, family or carer's responsibilities, pregnancy, religion, political opinion, national extraction, social origin, and experience of family and domestic violence). This applies to questions asked of referees and to how check results are used; a defence applies where the person could not perform the inherent requirements of the job. Federal, state and territory anti-discrimination Acts add further grounds. Criminal record is not a protected ground under the federal Sex/Race/Disability/Age Discrimination Acts, but the Australian Human Rights Commission can investigate \"criminal record\" discrimination in employment under the AHRC Act 1986 (drawing on ILO Convention 111) — though it cannot make binding orders; an employer should only rely on a criminal record where it is genuinely relevant to the inherent requirements of the particular job, and NT and Tasmania expressly make \"irrelevant criminal record\" discrimination unlawful, while WA and ACT have spent-conviction protections. (3) Background checks: a Nationally Coordinated Criminal History Check (national police check, via ACIC-accredited bodies or police agencies) can only be run with the applicant's informed consent, given for a specific purpose, with fresh consent needed if the purpose changes. Child-related roles require a state/territory Working with Children Check (e.g. NSW WWCC, QLD Blue Card), which is mandatory and must be verified by the employer. (4) Respect@Work: since the December 2022 amendments, employers and PCBUs have a positive duty under the Sex Discrimination Act 1984 (Cth) (Part IIA, s 47C) to take reasonable and proportionate measures to eliminate, as far as possible, sexual harassment, sex discrimination and related conduct — relevant to keeping reference conversations and recruitment professional and non-discriminatory. This is general information, not legal advice; thresholds and state rules vary and a business should confirm its specific position.",
