      "summary": "In Australia, how an employer manages underperformance, misconduct and the ending of employment is governed primarily by the Fair Work Act 2009 (Cth), administered by the Fair Work Ombudsman (guidance/education) and the Fair Work Commission (dispute resolution). Two ideas run through this whole area: a valid reason (related to the employee's capacity or conduct) AND a fair process. For ordinary underperformance, fair process means clearly telling the employee what is wrong, giving them a real chance and reasonable time/support to improve, warning (preferably in writing) that their job is at risk if they don't, letting them respond, and allowing a support person at dismissal-related meetings. \"Misconduct\" sits on a spectrum: ordinary misconduct still requires warnings and process, while \"serious misconduct\" (as defined in the Fair Work Regulations 2009 reg 1.07 — e.g. theft, fraud, assault, sexual harassment, serious safety breaches, refusing a lawful and reasonable instruction) can justify summary dismissal (termination without notice), but only where the employer holds that belief on reasonable grounds and still affords basic procedural fairness. On ending employment, the National Employment Standards set minimum written notice periods (s117) scaled by length of service (with an extra week for employees 45+ with 2+ years' service); genuine casuals and those dismissed for serious misconduct are not entitled to notice. Unfair dismissal protection (s385–387) is available to employees who have served the minimum employment period — 6 months generally, but 12 months for a \"small business employer\" (fewer than 15 employees on a simple headcount, counting regular and systematic casuals). Small businesses get a safe harbour: if they follow the Small Business Fair Dismissal Code, the dismissal is deemed fair. Unfair dismissal claims must be lodged with the Commission within 21 days of the dismissal taking effect. A dismissal that is a \"genuine redundancy\" (s389 — job no longer required due to operational change, award/agreement consultation obligations met, and no reasonable redeployment) is not an unfair dismissal; redundancy pay (s119) is scaled by service, but small business employers (fewer than 15 employees) are generally exempt from redundancy pay — though they must still give notice, consult under any applicable award, and ensure the redundancy is genuine. Cutting across all of this, the general protections (adverse action) provisions make it unlawful to dismiss or harm an employee for a prohibited reason (exercising a workplace right, a discriminatory attribute, temporary illness/injury absence with evidence, etc.), so performance and disciplinary processes should be objective, documented and free of any prohibited motive. This is general information, not legal advice; thresholds, awards and individual contracts can change the outcome.",
