      "summary": "In Australia's national workplace relations system, the floor for what an employee can lawfully be paid is set by two interlocking instruments: the National Minimum Wage (for award/agreement-free employees) and modern awards (industry- or occupation-specific minimum rates and conditions). The Fair Work Commission (FWC) reviews and adjusts both each year in its Annual Wage Review, with changes taking effect from the first full pay period on or after 1 July. The 2026 review (decision handed down 2 June 2026) delivered a 4.75% increase to award minimum wages and set the National Minimum Wage at $1,004.90 per week / $26.44 per hour, operative from the first full pay period on or after 1 July 2026. Modern awards classify employees into graded levels that drive their minimum rate. The Manufacturing and Associated Industries and Occupations Award 2020 (MA000010) uses an engineering classification scale running from C14 (entry-level, lowest paid) up through C13, C12, C11, C10, C9 … to C1 (highest), where C10 is the trade-qualified benchmark or \"standard rate.\" A business that engages award-covered staff must pay at least the rate for the employee's correct classification, plus any applicable casual loading, penalty rates, overtime and allowances. Casual employees are defined by statute (Fair Work Act 2009 s.15A, as reshaped by the 2024 \"Closing Loopholes\" reforms) and are generally paid a 25% casual loading instead of paid leave entitlements; under MA000010 clause 11.1 that loading is 25%. Employers must keep prescribed time-and-wages records for 7 years and issue compliant pay slips within one working day of pay day. This is general information for an HR tool, not legal advice — wage rates change every July and award classification decisions are fact-specific, so users should confirm current rates via the Fair Work Ombudsman Pay and Conditions Tool and the award itself.",
