      "subtitle": "Work Health and Safety (WHS): model WHS Act/Regulations, primary duty of care, consultation, incident notification, and worker duties for Australian small businesses",
      "summary": "Work health and safety in most of Australia is governed by a harmonised \"model\" framework developed by Safe Work Australia and enacted in each jurisdiction as a Work Health and Safety Act 2011 plus Work Health and Safety Regulations 2011, supported by approved Codes of Practice. The Commonwealth, NSW, Queensland, SA, Tasmania, WA, the ACT and the NT have adopted the model laws; Victoria runs a separate but broadly similar regime under its Occupational Health and Safety Act 2004 (so Victorian section numbers differ). Section numbers cited here are from the model/Commonwealth WHS Act 2011 and are mirrored in the adopting states/territories.\n\nThe central obligation is the primary duty of care (s 19): a person conducting a business or undertaking (a \"PCBU\" — broadly, the business itself) must ensure, so far as is reasonably practicable, the health (physical and psychological) and safety of its workers and that other people are not put at risk by its work. \"Reasonably practicable\" (s 18) is judged by weighing the likelihood of harm, the degree of harm, what the person knows or ought to know about the risk and its controls, the availability/suitability of controls, and cost (which only excuses inaction if \"grossly disproportionate\" to the risk). Officers of the business (e.g. directors) have a separate due-diligence duty (s 27), and workers and other people at a workplace have their own duties to take reasonable care and follow reasonable instructions (ss 28–29).\n\nTwo operational pillars matter most for a small-business HR/safety tool. First, consultation: a PCBU must consult workers (and any health and safety representatives) so far as is reasonably practicable on matters affecting their health and safety (ss 47–49), and must consult, cooperate and coordinate with other duty holders who share a duty (s 46). Second, incident notification: the most serious work-related events — a death, a \"serious injury or illness,\" or a \"dangerous incident\" (ss 35–37) — must be notified to the WHS regulator immediately (s 38), with the incident site preserved until an inspector permits otherwise (s 39). Records of notifiable incidents must be kept for at least 5 years (s 38). From December 2025 the model laws were amended (the Model WHS Legislation Amendment (Incident Notification) 2025) to broaden what must be notified under a new umbrella term, a \"relevant occurrence\" — expanding the existing \"notifiable incident\" category (including certain violent incidents) and adding \"notifiable extended absences\" and \"notifiable suicides\" (including attempted/suspected suicide). Each jurisdiction adopts these model amendments on its own timeline (they apply only once enacted locally), so businesses should check their local regulator for the categories and timeframes currently in force. The Regulations add specific duties such as first aid (reg 42) and emergency plans (reg 43). Workers also have a limited right to cease, and HSRs a power to direct cessation of, unsafe work where there is a reasonable concern of serious risk (ss 84–85). This is general information, not legal advice; the precise duties and penalties depend on the jurisdiction whose WHS law applies.",
