      "id": "starting",
      "icon": "📄",
      "title": "Starting employment",
      "subtitle": "Starting Employment in Australia: Information Statements, Contracts, Casual Employment & Probation",
      "summary": "When a small Australian business hires someone, several legal obligations attach at the very start of employment, all flowing from the Fair Work Act 2009 (Cth) and the National Employment Standards (NES). Every new employee must be given the Fair Work Information Statement (FWIS) before they start or as soon as practicable after, and every new casual must additionally be given the Casual Employment Information Statement (CEIS) before, or as soon as practicable after, they start (and again at set intervals during employment). The employment contract sits on top of the legal safety net: it can add to entitlements but can never provide less than the NES, an applicable modern award or the national minimum wage — any term that tries to undercut the minimum simply has no effect.\n\nCasual employment was redefined from 26 August 2024 under the \"Closing Loopholes\" reforms. A person is a casual (s 15A) only if, at the time the employment offer is accepted, there is no firm advance commitment to continuing and indefinite work, assessed on the real substance, practical reality and true nature of the relationship (not just the written contract), and they are entitled to a casual loading or specific casual rate of pay. The old \"casual conversion\" model was replaced by an \"employee choice\" pathway: an eligible casual (employed at least 6 months, or 12 months in a small business) who believes they no longer meet the casual definition can give written notice to convert to permanent work; the employer must consult and respond in writing within 21 days, and may only decline on the casual definition still being met or on fair and reasonable operational grounds.\n\nFinally, \"probation\" and the \"minimum employment period\" are different things and businesses routinely confuse them. A probation period is a contractual arrangement the parties agree to — it has no standing under the Fair Work Act and does not change anyone's NES entitlements (employees keep accruing and accessing the same entitlements during probation). The minimum employment period, by contrast, is set by the Act (s 383): an employee generally cannot bring an unfair dismissal claim until they have completed 6 months of continuous service, or 12 months if they work for a small business employer (fewer than 15 employees). The minimum employment period applies regardless of what the contract's probation clause says, and other protections (such as general protections / unlawful termination) can still apply from the start of employment. This is general information, not legal advice.",
